Good legal scholarship should make (1) a claim that is (2) novel, (3) nonobvious, (4) useful, and (5) sound.
And the claim should (6) be seen by the reader to be novel, nonobvious, useful, and sound.

           -- Eugene Volokh in Academc Legal Writing (with acknowledgement to Stephen Carter)


