The Four Noble Truths of Statistics

1. There is no substitute for data.
2. All models are false, but some are useful.
3. Without assumptions, there can be no conclusions.
4. It is only possible to assess uncertainty, not to prove hypotheses.

The Noble Eightfold Path to Effective Statistical Reasoning

1. Right Comparison
2. Right Control of Nuisance Variables
3. Right Consideration of Alternative Explanations and Contrary \hbox to 0pt{Cases\hss}
4. Right Elimination of Bias
5. Right Display of Data and Conclusions
6. Right Clarification of Assumptions
7. Right Model Validation
8. Right Interpretation and Generalization


    -- Christopher R. Genovese

       [The first four are derived from an unattributed quote
        I heard at a lecture by Dr. Elizabeth Thompson. 
        I now believe that originally items 1-4 were stated by
        John Tukey. See below]

--------------------------------------------

Principles of Statistics

1. There is no substitute for data.
2. All models are false, but some are useful.
3. Without assumptions, there can be no conclusions.
4. It is only possible to assess uncertainty, not to prove hypotheses.

        John Tukey (from an unattributed quote by Dr. Elizabeth Thompson)

